node.title: Questions about the dependence of elastic tensor on phase field variable
node.bodyText:
Dear,
I am new to the moose and right now I am trying to couple the phase field and tensor mechanics to simlulate dendrite growth in elastic field. I am reading examples in the  modules/phase_field-mechanics/combined directory. I am confused about the way Moose specify the elastic tensor's dependence and strain's dependence on phase field varible.
For example, in the input file Conserved.i,
For elastic tensor, no field is reserved for the choice of phase variable in following section, but indeed elastic tensor is different across different phase field.

For strain and elastic energy, args are specified as c in the correponding section, but I cannot understand the way c interacts with strain and energy. I've read some official document on ComputeVariableEigenstrain and ElasticEnergyMaterial, but there seems to be no direct explanation.

Any reponse will be highly appreciated!
Best,
Zhigang

Just by reading that input file it seems to me that

the eigenstrain is defined as 0.1 * c * I, where I is the second order identity tensor;
the strain purely depends on the eigenstrain, hence the strain is defined as -0.1 * c * I; Nope, there's also elastic deformation.
the elasticity tensor is homogeneous (doesn't depend on c).
BTW, I'm not a fan of coupling "Eulerian" dendritic growth with "Lagrangian" mechanics. It's not as simple as it seems to be.

Dear hugary:
Thanks for the comments. Yeah, but it's wired the elasticity tensor is homogeneous since there are two saperate phases. As for the difficulty of coupling between Eulerian method and Lagrangian method, thanks for pointing out and I will think more about it.
Best
zhigang

I think that's a perfectly valid example for demonstration purposes. If you want to have variable dependent elasticity tensor you can use ComputeVariableElasticityTensor or something like that, I don't remember the exact name.

Best,

node.title: Plastic parameters that depend on space and time
node.bodyText:
Hello,
I’m trying to run slope stability simulations in tensor mechanics. In particular, I’m using the shear strength reduction method on a heterogenous material. For this method, I would need to have the friction angle and the cohesion in the Mohr-Coulomb model that both depend on space (given by a csv file) and time (all the Mohr-Coulomb parameters are reduced by the same factor at every time step).
I have tried to follow the solution used in Porous Flow to produce a heterogeneous reservoir:
https://mooseframework.inl.gov/modules/porous_flow/heterogeneous_models.html
This solution does not to be directly applicable in my case as the materials properties in this example that change with space (permeability and porosity) are declared as Auxvariables and are used in a Material. However, it seems that I cannot used Auxvariables in a UserObject, which is the current way to define the Mohr-Coulomb properties. I get the following error when compiling if I try to create a Userobject that could use the Auxvariable of the friction angle:
error: use of undeclared identifier 'coupledValue'; did you mean 'coupledScalar'?
It seems that only Scalar variables can be used in a UserObject.
Do you have some ideas how I could have those parameters depending on space and time (without changing the whole return map algorithm)?
Thanks for your help!

Hello
You need your class to be using the Coupleable interface to be able to use the coupledValue routine. This interface is inherited by Element/Side/Interface/etcUserObject, not by UserObject the parent class of all of these.
If your UO fits in one of these categories, please inherit those instead.
For parameters depending on space and time, you can use a Function if they are known at the time you are writing your input file. If they are to be computed during the simulation you can use:

a material property
an auxiliary variable if you dont need to take derivatives into account / the terms are not part of forming a Jacobian with automatic differentiation. OR if you need tight control on when to update the quantity (linear / nonlinear iterations / once a timestep etc)

Guillaume

Hi Guillaume,
Thanks a lot for your quick reply!
Regarding the solution you propose for the parameters that depend on space and time, it is what I’m trying to do. I’m using a function that is changing an AuxVariable for each parameter, but I’m stuck at using this AuxVar in a UO…
To be more precise, the UO I have created to have the plastic properties coming from an AuxVariable is a modified copy of the UO “TensorMechanicsHardeningConstant” (which takes constant parameters as input). The parent class of all UO that defines plastic parameters is “TensorMechanicsHardeningModel”, which inherits from GeneralUserObject and, as you suggested, it seems to be the issue here.
I have tried to have “TensorMechanicsHardeningModel” inherit from Element/Side/Interface/etcUserObject instead of GeneralUserObject, but it is creating 20 errors when compiling.
I also tried to #include different files (like "MooseVariable.h" and others) directly in the UO I have created, but it didn’t change anything.
I apologise my knowledge of C++ is quite limited...
Hadrien

node.title: Question about MOOSE Creep
node.bodyText:
Hi all:
Based on RadialReturnCreepStressUpdateBase  or  PowerLawCreepStressUpdate in MOOSE, we can realize creep calculation related to Von Mises stress . I want to know how to  realize  the creep calculation in MOOSE if the creep rate is related to the principal stress but not to Von Mises stress.
Thanks a lot!

Dear @echo1115
I think you need to change the expression for "effective_trial_stress" in RadialReturnStressUpdate
You can create another class with a different expression for the trial stress,
then two new classes derived from it like RadialReturnCreepStressUpdateBase and  PowerLawCreepStressUpdate
Nicolò

Right, I was expecting this. The isotropic creep model in tensor_mechanics assumes J2 plasticity. So if you modify the expression for effective trial stress, you also need to modify the discrete update. Your expression is equivalent to having a flow direction as a function of the spectrum of the stress, from which the discrete update should follow. There might be something tricky to implement though, because your flow direction isn't constant during the plasticity update.

I am not sure exactly which creep model are you using. For some cases, e.g. eqn 15 in https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0022311521000180 it is possible to derive an analytical expression in principal coordinate system, and then transform it back to the global coordinate system. For general case, you need to use a return mapping algorithm as suggested by @hugary1995  and @ngrilli

node.title: AC equation in phase field module
node.bodyText:
Hello guys,
I want to use this AC equation, but it is too complex, especially  the x in it.
AC equation:

Np:

x:

The number of terms of this AC equation is related to x.
My scheme is to use for and if in the residual to sum every term of etas( if eta_j>0).
It's not easy because M and other coefficients are constants but are different according to different phases...So tough.
What I could think of is to let them be added as arrays in the input file.  While there is only three phases and 3 different values, but for n grains, the array will be n*n.
Like M in .i file:
M_ij = '7e-8 7e-8 7e-8 7e-8
7e-8 7e-8 7e-8 e-6
7e-8 7e-8 7e-8 e-6
7e-8 e-6 e-6 7e-8'
Could anyone give me some ideas about there coefficients?

Answering this for the sake of closing the post since this was years ago.
MOOSE will let you input vectors and arrays in the input parameters. You can then unfold the vector in the matrix of coefficients you need in your user-code.
With regards to the model being complex, MOOSE can handle arbitrary numbers of variables and fully couple the equation solves. I think you will find this to be an advantage for your problem.
I would first start with a lot of repetition in the kernels to build the system, then once you have something working and correct if you need to shorten the syntax you can look into either:

using an action to generate the system
or
using array variables and array kernels to have less objects in the input file
